      "solution": "width = int(input())\ngap = int(input())\n\n# Makes a diamond with a given size, and aligned to another size\ndef make_diamond(w, a):\n    mid = w // 2\n    rows = []\n    for i in range(w):\n        if i <= mid:\n            c = 2 * i + 1\n        else:\n            c = 2 * (w - i) - 1\n        # Center within the width\n        rows.append(('#' * c).center(a, \".\"))\n    pad_top = (a - w) // 2\n    pad_bottom = a - w - pad_top\n    return [\".\" * a] * pad_top + rows + [\".\" * a] * pad_bottom\n\ndiamond = make_diamond(width, width)\ngap = make_diamond(gap, width)\n\n# An 'xor' like thing to remove the gap diamond\nfinal = []\nfor a, b in zip(diamond, gap):\n    row = \"\"\n    for x, y in zip(a, b):\n        row += x if y != \"#\" else \".\"\n    final.append(row)\n\nprint(\"\\n\".join(final))",
      "statement": "You must output a diamond with a gap in the center.\n\nThe diamond is drawn using {{#}} and the space (both inner and outer) is denoted by {{.}}\nEach of [[width]] lines should be a string of [[width]] length, containing either {{.}} or {{#}}\n\nThe [[gap]] is the dimension of hollowed space in the middle, replacing {{#}} with {{.}}\nThe gap is always centered within the diamond.\n\nWhen [[width]] and [[gap]] are equal, the result should be a [[width]] by [[width]] grid of {{.}}\nThe value of [[gap]] can be {{0}}, meaning the diamond is solid.\n\nMeasure the width of a diamond and its inner space using their respective diagonals. For example, a diamond of width 5:\n```..#..\n.###.\n#####\n.###.\n..#..```\n\nAs an example of the gap. An diamond with a width 5, and gap of 3:\n```..#..\n.#.#.\n#...#\n.#.#.\n..#..```",
